<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-541-202  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 541 202.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  June 4 1990 v4 n22 p34(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Typhoon Mac. (DefensePC)(desktop weather forecasts)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Lallande, Ann.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The US Joint Typhoon Warning Center, located at Air ForceDetachment 1, 1st Weather Wing in Agana Guam, is a pioneer ofcomputerized reception and analysis of satellite weather images.andO;Efforts have resulted in a tool to reduce the time to determinethe location and severity of a storm, and improve accuracy ofcalculations.andP;  With the help of a Macintosh IIx, tropical stormanalysis is now in an era of enhanced computer imaging at thebase.andP;  The system can determine cloud temperature at any point inthe satellite picture and can bring the satellite image andanalytical process to life by looping pictures and palettes ofmoving color.andP;  This type of calculation has previously been doneon more expensive microcomputer workstations and minicomputers.andO;Air Force Detachment 1 and the Joint Typhoon Warning Center arecharged with tracking storms over a large area of the earth'ssurface - 60 degrees to the north and 60 degrees to the south fromthe dateline to the east coast of Africa.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Product:   Apple Macintosh IIX (Microcomputer) (military use).andO;Topic:     MicrocomputersMeteorologySatellite CommunicationsGuamUnited States. Air Force.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>